@variant-of equity/confident-adaptation
@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@divergence The canonical equity/confident-adaptation pattern deepens this
via Sen (capability conversion), Sloman/Lovelace (informational
conversion as form-giving), and a Go-board-rules metaphor ("arrested
formation"). The paper itself does not carry that theoretical apparatus;
it names the scaffold, the actor, and the governance move, and stops
there. This variant records the paper's framing as published.

! conclusion: Trainers cannot adapt confidently without knowing what must be retained and what can be changed.  The programme should publish an expectation scaffold — a clearly enunciated stance on what is fixed (core topics, minimum delivery format, evaluation expectation) and what is flexible (local sequencing, depth, audience, delivery mode) — ideally produced by the training community rather than issued to them, so that trainers' confusion is converted into acts of governance rather than private compensation.
  + context: This is NPT Coherence — specifically 1.2 Communal Specification: a shared understanding of what is being done and why.  It is an intervention-tier pattern with low coordination: a central agency (the Training Project) can resolve it by producing and maintaining the scaffold.  The paper describes this as the most tractable of the five patterns.  Its absence is cited as a direct contributor to architectural mismatch mode; its presence is a precondition for multiplied input.
  + IF:
    A central programme trains intermediaries who deliver in varied local settings.  Trainers bring motivation and partial competence but enter without a shared understanding of what the programme actually requires — which elements are non-negotiable, which admit local variation, and what "ready to deliver" looks like.  The training's own community-and-research dimensions may be unknown to trainers who registered for the course alone.
  + HOWEVER:
    The programme has not published the fixed/flexible distinction.  Trainers report uncertainty about what was fundamental, how many sessions were required, and whether the courses were part of a research project (FG2A.15, FG2B.1; T2A: "It wasn't very clear to us how many sessions we needed to have attended, which ones were fundamental"; T2B: "I didn't realise when I first signed up for it that these courses were part of this research project").  Where the expectation was explicit, the programme became an "effective entry point" (FG3.4; T3: "It was useful to have a template of what was expected").  The gap is informational, not a skill gap — an absence of communal specification rather than an absence of capability.
  + THEN:
    The Training Project produces a central expectation scaffold that enunciates what is fixed and what is flexible.  Production is reconnoitred with trainers rather than issued to them: the scaffold converts their confusion into acts of governance and becomes revisable by the community that uses it.  The scaffold is not a compliance checklist; it is a minimum specification that makes local adaptation a formative act rather than guesswork.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT Coherence: 1.2 Communal Specification is the shared understanding that makes collective action possible.  Trainers reported high COM-B self-efficacy ("I understand what this requires of me" M=4.90) individually, but communal specification was absent at the programme level — which is what produces fragmented delivery even where individual capability is high.

    Tier and coordination: This is an intervention-tier failure that can be resolved at low coordination.  A single central actor (the programme team) is sufficient.  The paper is most prescriptive here because the pattern is most tractable.

    Governance framing: The scaffold is an act of governance rather than a directive.  The trainers' role in its production matters: a scaffold issued top-down converts into compliance; a scaffold reconnoitred with the community converts confusion into shared authorship of the programme's definition.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Publish the expectation scaffold before the next cohort
    - Produce it with trainers, not for them
    - Make the fixed/flexible distinction the scaffold's central content, not an annex
    - Design the scaffold as revisable so it remains a governance instrument rather than a decree
    - Test by asking a new trainer to explain what is expected after reading the scaffold alone
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    The programme publishes a current expectation scaffold stating what is fixed and what is flexible.  The scaffold is produced with trainer input and revised in light of their experience.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Missing scaffold: trainers guess what is essential and deliver fragmented versions
    - Scaffold-as-decree: scaffold exists but is issued without trainer input and becomes a compliance instrument
    - Frozen scaffold: produced once, never revised; drifts from practice
    - Scope invisibility: trainers unaware of the programme's research or community dimensions beyond the training itself
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 1: Confident Adaptation
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2A ("It wasn't very clear to us how many sessions we needed to have attended")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B ("I didn't realise when I first signed up that these courses were part of this research project")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("It was useful to have a template of what was expected")
    - Focus-group codes: FG2A.15, FG2B.1 (uncertainty); FG3.4 (where explicit, effective entry point)
    - COM-B: "I understand what this requires of me" M=4.90
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Coherence 1.2 Communal Specification as stated in the companion journal article.
    Tier: Intervention.  Coordination: Low (central agency).
    Implementation-mode link: absence contributes directly to architectural mismatch; presence is a precondition for multiplied input.
    The paper is most prescriptive here — the pattern is most tractable of the five.
